  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered an illegal practice?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered an illegal practice in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by disguising its true source. This is typically done by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make it difficult for law enforcement agencies to trace the origin of the funds to criminal activity.\n\nMoney laundering is often associated with crimes such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism financing. Because it undermines the integrity of financial systems and facilitates criminal activities, it is subject to strict legal penalties, including significant fines and imprisonment. Various international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), work to combat money laundering by setting global standards and promoting effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures.",
